<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Boromir Advantage<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.42)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=4425'>Michael "Bobafett465" Robinson</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=4425&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> August 10, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br>
<br>
	This article will be based around the strategic gameplay of one of the key players in the Fellowship, Boromir. Before I go in-depth about his value in playing a good deck, I would like to say something about the poor stereotyping that Decktech has created for my man Boromir. Everytime I read a deck whcih has strategy involving Boromir, they charcterize him as &quot;weak-willed&quot;, or a &quot;traitor&quot;. Well I can stand for this no longer. Frodo left the party because he know what happened to Boromir would eventually happen to everyone in the Fellowship, which it would have. His strong will to sace his people was simply the deciding factor in making him first to temporarily fall under the allure of the ring. Well, now that I have made my point, let us first explore the three current personas of Boromir.<br>
<br>
(3) Boromir, Son of Denethor<br>
Strength 7<br>
Vitality 3<br>
Skirmish: Exert Boromir to make a Hobbit strength +3.<br>
Frodo Signet<br>
<br>
This version is popular in Hobbit decks as it allows him to pump them up to an advantageous +3 strength. This works well with Merry, Friend to Sam. Get him to power 6, add a Hobit Sword, hes an 8, than win his skirmish first, add his 8 strength to maybe a Gandalf who than Servant of the Secret Fire&#39;s his minion, and overwhelms him. Not bad. Also, the prescence of the Frodo signet also allows him to exert to heal Frodo, Son of Drogo, another plus for Hobbit decks.<br>
<br>
(3) Boromir, Lord of Gondor<br>
Ranger.<br>
Strength 7<br>
Vitality 3 <br>
Boromir is not overwhelmed unless his strength is tripled.<br>
Aragorn Signet<br>
<br>
This version is nice in Large Fellowship decks, as his ability to last longer makes him key in the late game. Slap an armor on him, and an Elendil&#39;s Valor to make him Defender +1. Now he can take on the badies keepng your Frodo nice and safe. Maybe play a Swordarm of the White Tower to pump him to a strength +4. Nice. And he wont die because of the armor unless hes exhausted. Very cool.<br>
<br>
(3) Boromir, Defender of Minas Tirith<br>
Ranger.<br>
Strength 7<br>
Vitality 3<br>
Fellowship: Add 2 to heal Boromir.<br>
Gandalf Signet<br>
<br>
Now becoming a little more popular as Trust Me decks need more exposure to the Gandalf Signet, Defender of Minas Tirith (aptly named &quot;Death Trap&quot;) allows for a virtual mini-sanctuary for Boromir every turn. However, it doesnt come cheap at the cost of adding 2 to the pool. So, every turn seems to be a dilemna for his healing capability. Not great for Pool Denial decks, but for a Large Fellowship or other decks that give up alot of pool anyway, its not bad. Hey, in conjunction with Aragorn, Heir to the White City, you heal for free!<br>
<br>
Now lets take a look at some of the toys that Boromir can use to help him assist the Fellowship. From artifcats to possesions to events and conditions, there are a wealth of thing that can make Boromir a priceless character.<br>
<br>
(0) Horn of Boromir<br>
Possession<br>
Bearer must be Boromir.<br>
Manuever: Exert Boromir and spot an ally. Until the regroup phase, that ally is<br>
strength +3 and is involved in archery fire and skirmishes.<br>
<br>
Well obviously the first thing that comes to mind is this would be very useful is ally intensive decks. Can anyone say lets drag and unexpected strength 11 Elrond into the skirmish? Alright. This becomes huge at site 6 where your Calaglin, Orophin, and Rumil will already be involved. Why not drag in some of your old site 3 allies you forgot about? Elrond, maybe invincable Bilbo? (Consorting with Wizards anyone?) I know i know these ideas seem somewhat far-fetched but hey, original decks are always winners in my book.<br>
<br>
(1) Blade of Gondor<br>
Possession-Hand Weapon <br>
Strength +2<br>
Bearer must be Boromir. He is damage +1.<br>
Skirmish: Exert Boromir to wound an Orc or Uruk-Hai he is skirmishing.<br>
<br>
The Blade of Gondor was for a while widely considered the only thing that made Boromir worth playing. And rightly so. Adding 2 strength, and making him damage +1 is worth the 1 twilight. Also, the ability to auto-wound an Uruk-Hai or Orc is good if its lready exhausted or wounder from archery. Not bad.<br>
<br>
(1) Shield of Boromir<br>
Possession-Shield<br>
Bearer must be a Gondor companion. The minion archery total is -1. If bearer is Boromir,<br>
each minion skirmishing him does not gain strength bonuses from weapons.<br>
<br>
Awesome. First it solves some relatively stupid problems for the Fellowship. First, Uruk-Hai aren&#39;t really meant to be archery decks, in fact, its quite the opposite. But is that one archery point from Lurtz causing problems? No problem. Speaking of Uruk-Hai (and Nazgul), tired of the weapons like Pale Blade and Lurtz&#39;s Sword causing problems? No problem again. <br>
<br>
(0) Boromir&#39;s Cloak<br>
Possession-Cloak<br>
Bearer must be Boromir.<br>
Manuever: Exert Boromir to discard a weather condition.<br>
<br>
Well not many people play the cloak but while were talking about the B-man lets go into his other stuff. With the increase in popularity of Saruman&#39;s Snows because of PATHS/Hobbits decks, carrying this sucker around would be wse if the Snows,Chills or others are popular in your area.<br>
<br>
(1) Shards of Narsil<br>
Artifact<br>
Plays to your support area.<br>
Fellowship: Place a Gondor card here from hand.<br>
Fellowship: Add 1 to take a card stacked here into hand.<br>
<br>
Now the Shards arent really specific to Boromir, as people build entire decks around this great card. Stack cards for later use is one of the freeing aspects of the game, as many of the previous expansions lacked such a liberating mechanic. The lack of clog in your hand can allow late game Gondor decks to make room for early game Shadow decks. Comabined with the more game intensive Still Sharp, Boromir now seems a little more useful.<br>
<br>
(0) Still Sharp<br>
Event<br>
Spot the Shards of Narsil to make a Gondor companion strength +3 and damage +1. <br>
<br>
Awesome. Imagine this. Boromir, Defender of Minas Tirith with Blade of Gondor. Not bad right? Strength 9, Damage +1. Now, lets say yer playing a Shards deck. Now hes strength 12 and damage +2. HUGE. And the great part of the Shards is allowing you to put cards like Elendils Valor to put on him later. So Elendil&#39;s Valor makes him Defender +1 and SOTWT makes him strength +4. I know now were getting a little out of hand, but with the Shards, anything can be set up.<br>
<br>
	Well that about wraps up my first edition of the Boromir Advantage, expect another article this Novmeber on his brother Faramir.  <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3956&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
